Second Lieut. William Rawson, 2d U. S. Cavalry, class of 1869, at Forest Home, Miss., Sept. 1, 1869.

Lieut. Rawson had intended to start to join his regiment on the morning of the 1st of September, but feeling ill, he concluded to delay doing so. His symptoms at first caused no alarm, but later in the day his disease developed into a congestive chill, from the effects of which he died the same afternoon. The announcement of his death is preserved, as follows:

IN MEMORIAM.

Died of congestive chills, on Sept. 1, 1869, at his residence, Forest Home, Mississippi, Lieutenant William Rawson, U. S. A., after a brief illness of one day.

"Thou wilt not leave us in the dust;
Thou madest man—he knows not why;
He thinks he was not made to die;
And Thou hast made him: Thou art just."
